Short-Term Demand Evolution of Videos and Streamers on Twitch

Computer Systems and Performance Evaluation

Amirabbs Jalali - amj301

Introduction.

Nowadays, lots of content are going to be streamed online, and they can be reached simply by web browsers on any device. Twitch was the first platform that exclusively designed for live streaming video games from every game device. For instance, game consoles, mobile phones, etc. In this paper, I aim to find the evolution of the most popular trends in games and how the number of followers for streamers grows in this platform. At last, I want to statistically test some hypotheses about this system to find a better understanding of user behaviour and how to help this system to adapt to these trends.

The Datasets.

In this section, I will talk about the datasets that I used in this paper. First, I used one day period for finding trends and overview. After that, I used 2 weeks periods to find out the difference when it comes to a more extended period. The 2 weeks dataset is available on https://clivecast.github.io/. The original dataset covers a month with 5 minutes sample rate, but it is a huge dataset. To make that computational feasible, I only use 2 weeks with a 1-hour sampling rate. One day period dataset is available on https://github.com/Codecademy/datasets/tree/master/twitch and gathered by Codecademy and Twitch Science Team. The 2 weeks dataset is not completely clean, especially in the game name column there are lots of inconsistencies, for example, some games present in the dataset with full name and their abbreviation name. Consequently, I have to found those games and eliminate this issue. It is impossible to do this for all of the games, but it can be achieved for the most popular games. I check these games and manually remove those inconsistencies. For other games, I try to give them a specific format; I change all characters to lower case and then remove all the punctuations to increase game names consistency.

Experiments.

In this section, I will answer some questions about demand evolution in Twitch.

One day demand evolution of most popular games

In this part, I try to plot the most popular games demand evolution in one day. As you can see in this plot, the games are roughly going to be on their peak at the same time slot. It makes sense because people usually spend time on their hobbies after working hours and its true for both streamers and watchers side. The are some more interesting points in this plot, and its the nature of these games. When two games in the same genre come to be streamed, the difference between the games fan starts to be bold. As you can see, Dota 2 and LOL are both MOB games, but these games have completely different fans. LOL usually played by juniors, it is easy to play, and it is less brutal than Dota 2. On the other hand, Dota 2 is extremely hard to play, and lots of seniors play this game. Consequently, these games are completely opposite of each other. Other nature of the games is about the scariness of the game. Scary video games are usually played at midnight because they usually get more audiences at that time period.

Short-term demand evolution of most popular games

In this part, I expand the length of the period to two weeks to see how the trends fluctuate. I find that the one-day results are roughly the same, and those characteristics remain in two weeks periods. 

library(lubridate)
library(dplyr)

library(tm)

stream_evo = datalist %>%
  select('created_time',
         'game',
         'current_views',
         'total_views',
         'broadcaster_name',
         'followers_number',
         'language',
         'web_language',
         'broadcaster_created_time',
         'bitrate',
         'resolution') %>% 
  mutate(game = tolower(game)) %>% 
  mutate(game = removePunctuation(game)) %>%
  mutate(time = as.numeric(as.POSIXct(created_time,
                                      format="%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),units="secs"))

stream_evo_cut = stream_evo %>% mutate(cuts = cut(time, breaks = 336)) %>% 
  group_by(game) %>% 
  mutate(popularity = sum(current_views)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(game, cuts) %>% 
  summarize(popularity = mean(popularity), n = sum(current_views)) %>% 
  mutate (time = as.numeric( 
    sub("[^,]*,([^]]*)\\]", "\\1", cuts)), 
    time = as.POSIXct(time, origin = "1970-01-01", tz = "EST")) %>% 
  filter(popularity > 8000000, game != '1')

ggplot(data=stream_evo_cut, aes(x=time, y=n, colour=game)) +
  geom_line() +
  ggtitle("Trend of most popular games in one day") + 
  xlab("Date and Time") +
  ylab("Number of viewers") +
  facet_grid(game~.)

Short-term demand evolution of Twitch platform

In this part, I want to show when users use this platform and when this platform meets its peeks. It was evident that in a 24-hour time span, you can see a sine shape of usage and that because of most peoples behaviours. People usually start to spend time on their hobbies after working time, and they go to sleep after a while. As a result, in the evening, Twitch catches the maximum users and minimum usage in the mornings.

Streamers followers number evolution

In this part, I want to see how the number of followers changes for any streamers. There are lots of streamers with a big range of follower numbers, so if I want to show them all in one plot, it is nearly impossible that this plot shows some full meaning information. To tackle this problem, I divide streamers based on their follower numbers in three-tier. Low tier includes streamers with 100 to 1000 followers. Mid-tier includes streamers with 10000 to 500000 followers, and high tier includes streamers with more than 500000 followers.

Low-Tier

In this plot, it is clearly visible that no one lost followers, and the number of new followers is in O(#followers). 

flwr_evo = stream_evo %>% 
  filter(followers_number > 0) %>% 
  group_by(broadcaster_name) %>% 
  mutate(max_followers = max(followers_number)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(cuts = cut(time, breaks = 336)) %>% 
  group_by(broadcaster_name, cuts) %>% 
  summarise(followers_mean = max(followers_number), max_followers = mean(max_followers)) %>%
  mutate (time = as.numeric( 
    sub("[^,]*,([^]]*)\\]", "\\1", cuts)), 
    time = as.POSIXct(time, origin = "1970-01-01", tz = "EST"),
    num_time = as.numeric(as.POSIXct(time,
                                      format="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"),units="secs"))

low_tier = flwr_evo %>% 
  filter(100<max_followers & max_followers<1000) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(broadcaster_name) %>% 
  mutate(diff = max(followers_mean) - min(followers_mean)) %>% 
  filter(diff > 470, diff < 480)

ggplot(data=low_tier, aes(x=time, y= followers_mean, colour= broadcaster_name)) +
  geom_line() +
  ggtitle("Streamers' followers number evolution") + 
  xlab("Date and Time") +
  ylab("Number of followers") +
  scale_x_datetime(breaks = date_breaks("8 hours"), date_labels = "%b %d %H:%M") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

Mid-Tier

In this plot, it is visible that no one lost followers, and the number of new followers is in O(#followers) too. Interestingly, lots of these streamers have the same pace in gaining followers. 

mid_tier = flwr_evo %>% 
  filter(100000<max_followers & max_followers<500000) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(broadcaster_name) %>% 
  mutate(diff = max(followers_mean) - min(followers_mean)) %>% 
  filter(diff > 20000, diff < 40000)

ggplot(data=mid_tier, aes(x=time, y= followers_mean, colour= broadcaster_name)) +
  geom_line() +
  ggtitle("Streamers' followers number evolution") + 
  xlab("Date and Time") +
  ylab("Number of followers") +
  scale_x_datetime(breaks = date_breaks("8 hours"), date_labels = "%b %d %H:%M") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

High Tier

In this plot, it is visible that no one lost followers, and the number of new followers is in O(#followers) too. Interestingly, lots of these streamers have the same pace in gaining followers, and if you consider the number of new followers for every streamer in this tier, this function would be roughly linear. 

 high_tier = flwr_evo %>% 
  filter(500000<max_followers & max_followers<10000000) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(broadcaster_name) %>% 
  mutate(diff = max(followers_mean) - min(followers_mean))

ggplot(data=high_tier, aes(x=time, y= followers_mean, colour= broadcaster_name)) +

Hypotesis Tests.

In this section, I will try to prove some hypotheses by some statistical tests.

Anonymous viewers vs.subscribers

In this part, I test that if you have more followers, you will get more views. A correlation test can prove it, the result shows that they are highly correlated to each other. 

anms_scbr = streams %>% 
  group_by(subscriber) %>% 
  summarize(n = n()) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  mutate(n = n*100/sum(n)) 
  
anms_scbr %>% hchart(type='pie', hcaes(x=subscriber, y=n), name='%') %>% hc_xAxis(title=list(text='Is the user subscried to streamer?'))
anms_scbr_hist = streams %>% 
  group_by(channel, subscriber) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  summarize(total = n()) %>% 
  mutate(t_tf = sum(total))

ggplot(anms_scbr_hist, aes(x=reorder(channel, total), y=total, fill=subscriber)) +
  geom_col() +
  ggtitle("Subscribers vs. Anonymous in most popular streamers") + 
  xlab("Streamer Name") +
  ylab("Number of viewers")

anms_scbr_hist_t = anms_scbr_hist %>% 
  filter(subscriber == 'true')
cor.test(anms_scbr_hist_t$total, anms_scbr_hist_t$t_tf)

    Pearson's product-moment correlation

Streamers membership lenght vs.number of followers

In this part, I test that if you have more experience on this platform, you will have more followers. As the result shows, it is not true at all with very high precision. 

stream_evo_age = stream_evo %>% 
  group_by(broadcaster_name) %>% 
  mutate(max_flwr = max(followers_number),
         created_time_num = as.numeric(as.POSIXct(broadcaster_created_time, 
                                                  format="%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),
                                       units="secs")) %>% 
  summarise(max_flwr = mean(max_flwr), created_time_num = mean(created_time_num)) %>% 
  filter(max_flwr > 0) %>% 
  mutate(created_time_num_norm = created_time_num - min(created_time_num) + 1)

cor.test(stream_evo_age$max_flwr, stream_evo_age$created_time_num_norm)

    Pearson's product-moment correlation

data:  stream_evo_age$max_flwr and stream_evo_age$created_time_num_norm
